    <title>PeanutButter.Utils</title>
    <authors>Davyd McColl</authors>
    <owners>Davyd McColl</owners>
    <description>
      Provides an easy mechanism for writing win32 polling services:
      1. inherit from Shell
      2. Set ServiceName, Description and Interval (and optionally, Version)
      3. override RunOnce, providing the per-poll logic
      4. in your Main method, ensure you run your implementation:
      ```csharp
      int Main(string[] args)
      {
        return Shell.RunMain&lt;MyService&gt;(
          args
        );
      }
      ```
      
      Shell will poll on the set interval, preventing multiple simultaneous
      runs - so if the last poll took longer than the interval, the next poll
      will happen immediately after this one finishes.
      
      By including step 4, you also gain access to commandline handlers to
      manipulate the service:
      - start
      - stop
      - restart
      - install
      - uninstall
      - run once (test the logic, or to run as a regular process, scheduled by something else)
    </description>
